I"”
<p>The initial velocity has an upward direction, which is opposite to the direction of the gravitational acceleration. Thus, the object is decelerating ($a=-g$). And note that at the peak of flight, the object has an instantaneous velocity of 0 m/s. From the given parameters, we can simply solve the problem using $\eref{eq:kinematic eqn gravity 1}$,</p>

<figure style="text-align: center;">
  <img src="/images/content/phys1/phys1-3.4.2.png" alt="my alt text" width="250px" />
  <figcaption><em>
</em></figcaption>
</figure>

\[\begin{align*}
	v_f &amp;= v_i+gt
\end{align*}\]

<p>Since the ball is decelerating, $g$ must be negative. Thus,</p>

\[\begin{align*}
	v_2 &amp;= v_1+(-g)t \\
	v_2 &amp;= v_1-gt \\
\end{align*}\]

<p>Rearranging the equation gives us,</p>

\[\begin{align*}
	t &amp;= \frac{v_2-v_1}{-g} \\
	&amp;= \frac{0-15\un{m/s}}{-9.81 \un{m/s^2}} \\
	&amp;= 1.53 \un{s}		\tagans
\end{align*}\]

